<exercise xml:id="ex_draining_tank">
      <title>Modeling a draining tank</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <xref ref="fig_draining_tank"/> depicts a water tank in the shape of a circular cone (with tip pointed downward). The height of the tank is 4 meters, and its circular top has a radius of 2 meters. The tank contains an initial quantity of water that steadily drains through a regulated valve at the bottom.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig_draining_tank">
          <caption>A draining conical tank</caption>
          <image width="30%" source="APCFigure1-1-8.png"/>
        </figure>
        <p>
          Once the draining begins we record at each subsequent minute <m>t</m> the measurements of the height <m>h</m> (in meters), radius <m>r</m> (in meters), and volume <m>V</m> (in cubic meters) of the conical body of water remaining in the tank. These are summarized in <xref ref="table_draining_tank"/>.
        </p>
        <table xml:id="table_draining_tank">
          <title>Measurements of a draining water tank</title>
          <tabular>
            <col/><col/><col/><col/><col/><col/>
            <row>
              <cell right="minor"><m>t</m> (min)</cell> <cell>0</cell> <cell>1</cell> <cell>2</cell> <cell>3</cell> <cell>4</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell right="minor"><m>h</m> (m)</cell> <cell>3</cell> <cell>2.5</cell> <cell>2</cell> <cell>1.5</cell> <cell>1</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell right="minor"><m>r</m> (m)</cell> <cell>1.5</cell> <cell>1.25</cell> <cell>1</cell> <cell>0.75</cell> <cell>1</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell right="minor"><m>V</m> (m<m>^3</m>)</cell> <cell></cell> <cell></cell> <cell></cell> <cell></cell> <cell></cell>
            </row> 
          </tabular>
        </table>
        <p>
          It is evident that at any time <m>t</m> since the draining has begun, the height, radius, and volume of the remaining water have determinate values. Thus we have well-defined functions <m>h=f_1(t)</m>, <m>r=f_2(t)</m>, and <m>V=f_3(t)</m> that output the height, radius, and volume of the remaining water <m>t</m> minutes after draining has begun.  
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              What is an appropriate domain <m>D</m> for the functions <m>f_1,f_2,f_3</m>? Our table only provides values of the functions for <m>t\in \{0,1,2,3,4\}</m>. Does this mean we should set <m>D=\{0,1,2,3,4\}</m>? (There is not one correct answer here.)   
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Focus on the measurements of the height <m>h</m> of the remaining water. How does the height change with each passing minute? Conjecture a formula for the function <m>h=f_1(t)</m>. 
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The table suggests a relation between the height <m>h</m> and radius <m>r</m> of the remaining water at any given time. Express this as an equation involving <m>h</m> and <m>r</m>. Assuming your conjectured formula for <m>f_1</m> is correct, derive a formula for <m>r=f_2(t)</m>. 
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The volume formula for cylinders tells us that <m>V=\frac{1}{3}\pi r^2\, h</m>.
              <aside>
                <p>
                  This conical volume formula <m>V=\frac{1}{3}\pi r^2\, h</m> is nontrivial, and in fact its derivation requires some sophisticated calculus techniques: techniques you will be equipped with by the end of this course!
                </p>
              </aside>
              Assuming your conjectured formula for <m>f_1</m> is correct, compute a formula for <m>V=f_3(t)</m>. Assess the accuracy of your formula by comparing its outputs with <xref ref="table_draining_tank"/>.  
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              You have now modeled the various quanties associated to the remaining water with the functions <m>f_1,f_2, f_3</m>. Assess whether your model gives a sensible answer to the following question: what is the volume of the remaining water 10 minutes after the draining has begun? What, in the face of the evidence given by <xref ref="table_draining_tank"/>, is a plausible answer to this question. What is a natural way of adjusting your model so that it provides this answer?  
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    
